Rod Wave

About

Rod Wave is a 25 year old American hip hop, R&B, and trap soul rapper, singer, and songwriter. His real name is Rodarius Marcell Green, and he was born in Florida, USA. He has been active since 2016. In this time, he has created 5 mixtapes, 5 studio albums total, including 2 deluxe versions. Mixtapes are a more casual production of music, while studio albums are usually produced by professionals. His albums and mixtapes include:

Analysis

Setting Up

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)

df = read.csv("Rod Wave_data.csv")

Some of the track names are duplicated because there is a âdeluxe versionâ of some albums. Therefore, I removed these duplicates. I also changed the data type of the album from numeric to character.

# Removing records that have the same track name 
df <- df |> distinct(track_name, .keep_all = TRUE)

# Change the data type of album_name from numeric to character
df$album_name <- as.character(df$album_name)

Data Overview

This data was obtained by Joy Lee using the SpotifyR package. This table provides an overview of the downloaded data. Here is a description of the variables included:

  • Valence (positiveness): 0 = very negative, 1 = very positive

  • Energy: timbre, onset rate, entropy

  • Danceability: beat strength, regularity

  • Loudness: decibels

  • Speechiness: presence of spoken words

  • Instrumentalness: presence of non-vocal instrumental sound

  • Liveness: presence of an audience

  • Tempo: beats per minute (BPM)

  • Key mode: major vs.Â minor

This is a sample of the data that is being analyzed for this project.

Album Analysis (Valence and Energy)

For an overview, lets first identify if Rod Waveâs albums tend to be more energetic and positive, or not.

ggplot(df, aes(x = valence, y = energy, color = album_name)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0.5, color = "grey") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0.5, color = "grey") +
  labs(title = "Relationship Between Valence and Energy", x = "Valence", y = "Energy", color = "Album Name") +
   theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Visually, it appears that most albums are high energy and have a slightly lower valence level. Lets take a look at the most valent and energetic albums individually.

df$album_name <- as.factor(df$album_name)

ggplot(df, aes(x = album_name, y = energy)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  ggtitle("Rod Wave's Albums: Energy") +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) + #center title
  labs(x = "Album Name", y = "Energy") +
  scale_x_discrete(labels = function(x) lapply(strwrap(x, width = 10, simplify = FALSE), paste, collapse="\n")) #wrap lables

From this, we can tell that Rod Waveâs most energetic albums are Hunger Games 2, Hunger Games 3, and Jupiter Diary: 7 Day Theory. His least energetic album is Ghetto Gospel.

df$album_name <- as.factor(df$album_name)

ggplot(df, aes(x = album_name, y = valence)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  ggtitle("Rod Wave's Albums: Valence") +
    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
  labs(x = "Album Name", y = "Valence") +
  scale_x_discrete(labels = function(x) lapply(strwrap(x, width = 10, simplify = FALSE), paste, collapse="\n"))

Here, we can tell that Rod Waveâs albums with the lowest valence level is Nostalgia. On the other hand, the albums with the highest valence levels are Hunger Games 3, Ghetto Gospel, and Hunger Games 2. Lets take a look at the songs in these albums.

Now, I am interested to see if the tempo of Rod Waveâs songs have a relationship with its danceability.

ggplot(df, aes(x = danceability, y = tempo, color = album_name)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Danceability vs. Tempo", x = "Danceability", y = "Tempo (BPM)", color = "Album Name") +
   theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

It seems like the songs do not necessarily need to have a high tempo to be danceable, however, many do.
